answer: Have you tried this? I have a custom [thread with its own runloop](https://github.com/dashesy/pyavfcam/blob/develop/src/modules/avf_impl.m) and still `AVFoundation` comes through main run loop. If main run loop is blocking, it will not come (I am talking about OSX not iOS).

Your suggestion doesn't help because that property does not exist on iOS 8. He's asking how to handle when symbols don't exist, not how to test for specific featuresthe tests themselves are important in other ways, but don't exist on earlier versions of the platform.
@NamanGala thanks How about the first bullet point?
I was looking for a good way to encapsulate the code so that it could be performant as well as functional. Objects were the way to go. :D
And how do I use the Lifted class?

this one won't work then second time, I am not sure where its going wrong, but once you call mySerialize() on the form and then you call mySerialize() again it won't work, it works only the first time.

Why do you use the Thread class instead of wrapper like AsyncTask class? Robolectric has already a mechanism to avoid parallel code execution when using AsyncTask. `Robolectric.flushBackgroundThreadScheduler()` can only have an effect when you use a mechanism which can easy be shadowed by robolectric like AsyncTask.

You might check this question for some discussion of this: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6774624/does-using-namespaces-affect-performance-or-compile-time. As is said there, it cannot affect runtime performance. If you look at generated IL code, you'll see that it always uses full type name. The `using` statements only help keep you code cleaner, but the compiler effectively removes them.

import time
import random

arr = []

db = client.one

mycol = client["coll"]



while True:
    cursor = db.mycol.find()
    for document in cursor:
        print(document['num'])
    time.sleep(2)

MongoDB Indexes and Views

I'm having trouble finding much information on MongoDB's use of indexes when querying views. The docs state:

Index Use and Sort Operations

Views use the indexes of the underlying collection.

As the indexes are on the underlying collection, you cannot create, drop or re-build indexes on the view directly nor get a list of indexes on the view.

You cannot specify a $natural sort on a view.

aaaand that's about it. I'm trying to figure out how to properly index my underlying collections (based on my experience with SQL DBs) to maximize performance of my app's queries on views.

For example, let's say I have a collection holding Product entities in a products collection and which share deleted and categoryId attributes. On top of that I might create a view productsActive defined as { deleted: false }, and as such on an index on the products collection: { deleted: 1 }. Now let's say that I commonly do the following query:

db.productsActive.find({categoryId: 'turntable'});

Intuitively I want to use a compound index here on the products table:

db.products.createIndex({deleted: 1, categoryId: 1});

Am I doing it right? I suppose ultimately I'm confused by the doc's statement:

Views use the indexes of the underlying collection.

Given that, can mongo use the compound index to initially build the view and then to subsequently query it? Or is simply deriving the view one step (tied to 1 index) and then the subsequent query on the view a second, distinct query with its own index(es)?
answer: Accepting for this solution "name.sub(/^([^-]*-)/, "\\1one-")" as one is also variable here and need to be interpolated at some time. Please remove other optimal way to be precise with solution.
